<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0835-B"><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>This would present the possibility that even if a player swore off steroids after using them once, he still could eventually face a lifetime ban if regularly tested under Selig's proposal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051018.0568"><line>A total of 11 major leaguers have been suspended for violating MLB's drug policy this year.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="28" label="Eleven players were suspended for steroids in 2005" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>U.S. Attorney Kevin Ryan in San Francisco has said the plea deals were spurred in part by weak steroid laws and by the fact that some of the chemicals were not banned at the time.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>&quot;We're going to let the letter speak for itself and make no further comment,&quot; said Rob Manfred, Major League Baseball's top labor lawyer and the man who oversees the drug policy.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>After three offenses, they have no place in it.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>He said MLB will await publication of the book, &quot;Game of Shadows,&quot; which is due out March 23, then decide how to proceed.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>Palmeiro, one of four players in baseball history with 3,000 hits and 500 home runs, was suspended for 10 days in August for his positive test after his grievance was denied by an arbitration panel.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>The players union is expected to balk at the proposal.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="21,32,43"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>The New York Times reported last month that Palmeiro tested positive for the anabolic steroid stanozolol which is most notably linked to the Olympic sprinter Ben Johnson of Canada.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="27" label="Rafael Palmeiro tested positive" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>Major League Baseball slugger Barry Bonds could face a suspension if new claims detailing a history of doping are proven true, the Chicago Tribune reported Thursday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="21,23,51"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>The U.S. government has stepped in to investigate steroid use among professional baseball players use because it felt the sport wasn't doing enough to enforce its own policies.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="10,22,29"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>Greg Anderson, Bonds' trainer, was sentenced to six months after pleading guilty to money laundering and a steroid distribution charge.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051018.0568"><line>New York Mets pitcher Felix Heredia, who appeared in just three Major League Baseball games last season, became the fifth reliever to be suspended for violating the new steroid policy.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="11,41,57"><scu uid="18" label="Felix Heredia drew a 10-day steroid test suspension" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>&quot;As commissioner, you have the essential responsibility to safeguard the integrity of the game and to ensure that cheaters have no place in professional baseball,&quot; Cliff Stearns said in the letter.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>&quot;Major League Baseball and the players' association greeted word of our inquiry first as a nuisance, then as a negotiation, replete with misstatements,&quot; committee chairman Tom Davis said in his opening statement.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>After his positive steroid test, Palmeiro told an arbitration panel that he never &quot;intentionally&quot; used steroids.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="20"><scu uid="20" label="Palmiero denied intentionally taking the drug" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Instead of the current 10-game suspension for first offenders, Selig proposes a 50-game suspension in a 162-game season.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>Anderson and Conte remain free on bond and are scheduled to surrender to prison authorities on Dec. 1.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051018.0568"><line>Righthander Carlos Almanzar of the Texas Rangers was banned earlier this month for the first 10 days of the 2006 season.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="19" label="Carlos Almanzar received a 10-day steroid test suspension" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>Three federal judges backed the union last year with rulings that said the government improperly used search warrants, preventing the government from keeping urine samples and identifying paperwork linking them to players.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>&quot;Obviously the committee has the authority to conduct investigations.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>Among those accused is San Francisco Giants outfielder Barry Bonds, who broke the single-season home run record in 2001 and is closing on career leaders Hank Aaron and Babe Ruth.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>Last month, the authorities raided a laboratory in Champaign, Illinois headed by Patrick Arnold, who's known for introducing the steroid precursor androstenedione to the U.S. Andro came to public attention in 1998 when St. Louis Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire said he used it when breaking MLB's home run record.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>The commissioner is proposing suspending players for nearly one-third of a season for a first offense.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>Major League Baseball commissioner Bud Selig asked players to agree to a 50-game suspension for first-time steroid offenders and a lifetime ban for a third violation under what he called a &quot;three strikes and you are out approach&quot; to doping.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="7" sums="11,13,16,23,35,41,49"><scu uid="5" label="Proposed penalties include a 50-game suspension for the first offense" weight="4"/><scu uid="6" label="Proposed penalties include a lifetime ban for the third offense" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051018.0568"><line>The suspension will begin at the start of the 2006 campaign.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Although steroid use is believed rampant in many sports, baseball has taken the brunt of the controversy, in part because many past and present star sluggers -- including Barry Bonds, Mark McGwire, Jason Giambi and Gary Sheffield -- have been linked to use of the illegal substance.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="22,5"/></line><line>&quot;Whoever would be stupid enough to get caught once would surely stop under this new proposal,&quot; said Colorado Rockies pitcher Jason Jennings.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>&quot;I understand their desire to avoid the public's prying eye....</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>But it is still unsure if the substance has been linked to his positive steroid test.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Baseball's revised steroid testing program has suspended four players in two months.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="25"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>Conte, who will spend four months in prison and four months in home confinement, started the Bay Area Laboratory Co-Operative.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>&quot;I think they misjudged the will of an American public who believes that sunshine is the best disinfectant.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>Last week, Selig wouldn't commit to investigating.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>For a fifth positive, the penalty is at the commissioner's discretion.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>The case prompted U.S. pro sports to stiffen anti-doping policies and thrust performance-enhancing drugs into the spotlight.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>&quot;We'll respond in due course,&quot; Fehr said, adding he anticipated replying early next week.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>&quot;There is a pyramid of steroid use in society and today our investigation starts where it should _ with the owners and players at the top of that pyramid,&quot; Waxman said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>He also asked the union to ban amphetamines, to have more frequent random tests and to appoint an independent person to administer the MLB drug-testing program.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>McGwire set the single-season home run record with 70 in 1998, and Bonds broke it three years later with 73.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="3"/></line><line>In the initial steroid policy implemented last season, first offenders were not punished and players were tested just once.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="51"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>&quot;We have an ongoing investigation.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>Johnson was stripped of his gold medal in 1988 after testing positive for that steroid.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Instead of the current 30-game suspension for second-time offenders, Selig wants the penalty increased to 100 games.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>The lab, according to court records, counted dozens of prominent athletes among its clients, including Olympic track champion Marion Jones, major league baseball's Barry Bonds and Jason Giambi, and others.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>The players also could argue that early indications of the current drug-testing policy is it's the best among the four major sports.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="19,32"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>Citing two unnamed sources, the Baltimore Sun reported Thursday that Palmeiro told the panel of the substance.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Three strikes, and a player is out.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>I recognize the need for progressive discipline, but a third-time offender has no place in the game,&quot; Selig wrote to Fehr.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>Bonds is 47 home runs shy of Hank Aaron's all-time major league record of 755 career homers as he prepares for what he has said would be his farewell season.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>The 40-year-old Palmeiro is hitting.266 with 18 homers and 60 RBI in 100 games this season.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>&quot;Congress is so adamant about cleaning up steroids in baseball, they ought to clean up some of the stuff they're doing,&quot; said Rockies outfielder Dustan Mohr.</line><line>&quot;The use of such substances... (present) a fundamental challenge to the integrity of the game.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>The newspaper said Selig is expected to announce the decision next week, but hadn't yet decided if the investigation will be done by Major League Baseball officials or outside investigators.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Union leaders are expected to argue that implementing even harsher penalties before the new one is two months old would leave the players worried that no matter what they do, it would never be enough.</line><line>As for getting his proposal to fly with the players, Selig may count on escalating pressure from the public and the House Government Reform Committee that chastised baseball officials at a March 17 hearing.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>According to published reports, Bonds told a federal grand jury he unknowingly used a steroid cream provided by the Bay Area Laboratory Co-Operative, which is at the center of a government investigation that also has implicated 100-meter world record holder Tim Montgomery and Olympic champion Marion Jones.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>Palmeiro had gone two-for-26 and played under intense scrutiny since returning from his 10-day suspension.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>Stearns' House Energy and Commerce subcommittee held hearings last year about steroid use and he introduced the Drug Free Sports Act, one of several bills that would have made U.S. sports leagues give players lifetime bans for a second or third doping offense.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Among the concerns that have been raised since baseball began formal drug testing last season is the realization that several steroid agents stay in a person's blood stream for six months or longer.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>The Tribune also reported that Selig met with Bonds during spring training in 2004 over concerns about claims that Bonds took steroids.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>Asked Sunday whether baseball officials knew about the probe, Davis responded: &quot;They do now.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>Stearns asked Selig for information about a 2004 meeting with Bonds, MLB's policy for addressing alleged steroid use if a player doesn't fail a drug test, and what Selig's authority is to investigate alleged steroid use.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="10,43,5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>Union officials, who agreed Tuesday to a tougher punishment program for steroid and amphetamine dope cheats, want samples and records to stay at the labs where they are stored rather than given to BALCO investigators, fearing a leak to the public as happened with the grand jury.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Selig also requested that amphetamines be added to the list of banned substances that includes steroids, steroid precursors, masking agents, ephedrine, Androstenedione and human growth hormone.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>He is due back in court later this month.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>You bring professional baseball players and the world comes to it,&quot; Davis told the CBS News program &quot;Face the Nation.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>Federal prosecutors are seeking access to urine samples taken from Major League Baseball (MLB) players in 2003 while the MLB Players Association fights to protect the identity of 104 steroid cheats.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="11,12,14,21,25,40,41,42,57"><scu uid="29" label="Steroid tests in 2003 showed 104 users" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>However, he could not explain how the drugs got into his body.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>Without immunity from prosecution, some players were thought to be considering invoking their Fifth Amendment right to refuse to answer questions.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>On Thursday a roster of baseball's heavy-hitters, including Mark McGwire, Rafael Palmeiro and Sammy Sosa, testified at the hearing.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>But that was before his legacy was soiled by the positive steroid test.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>BALCO head Victor Conte was sentenced to eight months on Tuesday as part of a plea deal for his role as mastermind behind a scheme to provide professional athletes with undetectable performance-enhancing drugs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Manfred did say Selig's proposals would become part of the minor-league steroid policy next season.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="6"><scu uid="11" label="These penalties would apply to minor-league players next year" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>Bonds, who broke Mark McGwire's season homer record in 2001 and is approaching Babe Ruth's career total, is accused in an upcoming book of using steroids, human growth hormone and insulin for at least five seasons beginning in 1998.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>Under the rules that began this season, a first offense gets a 10-day suspension, with the penalty increasing to 30 days for a second positive test, 60 days for a third and one year for a fourth.</line><line>MLB has no penalties for amphetamine use by players on major-league rosters, but are banned for players under minor league contracts.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="38,8"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>Selig sat with arms crossed and lips pursed as Davis and ranking minority member Henry Waxman chastised him and his sport.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Addressing his letter to players' union boss Donald Fehr last week, Selig said he wants to abolish the taint that the steroid controversy has brought to the national pastime.</line><line>&quot;Fifty games, that's a big hit.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>Still, authorities are now taking aim at the alleged BALCO suppliers.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>The New York Daily News, however, reported Thursday that Selig has already decided to begin an investigation, according to an unidentified baseball official.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>&quot;That's the first we heard of that,&quot; said Rob Manfred, an executive vice president with the league told CBS.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Under the current policy, players don't receive a lifetime ban until a fifth offense.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>Track coach Remi Korchemny is expected to get probation at a later sentencing date.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>Selig made a vague offer of leniency to Bonds if he had anything to confess, the Tribune reported, but also warned that consequences would be &quot;much worse&quot; if he proclaimed innocence and evidence blater revealed him as a steroid user.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Selig will no longer applaud or take pains to defend the current steroid policy, as he so fervently attempted during a contentious, 11-hour congressional hearing in March.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>THG, a once-unknown steroid discovered in the investigation, is now banned throughout sports.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>The proposal comes six weeks after several officials, players and former players testified before the U.S. Congress regarding MLB's doping policy following revelations by some and accusations of widespread steroid use within the league.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>&quot;I don't think we ought to negotiate things because the press wants us to.&quot;</line><line>&quot;I have grave concerns about the damage that has been done to Major League Baseball by players' use of performance-enhancing substances,&quot; Selig wrote to Fehr.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="3,36,37,49,6"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>Bonds was set to make his spring training debut Thursday for the Giants, two days after excerpts from the upcoming book &quot;Game of Shadows&quot; detailed a program of doping that began in 1998 and included his 2001 season, when he hit a one-season major league record of 73 homers.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>Samples and records from the 2003 survey were to have been destroyed, but when the BALCO steroid scandal began just before the end of the 2003 season, prosecutors filed subpoenas for all the samples and paperwork.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>Addressing the players, Davis said some &quot;have an opportunity today to either clear their name or take public responsibility for their action, and perhaps offer cautionary tales to our youth.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>Under pressure from Congress, MLB's players association agreed to toughen drug testing rules and penalties for 2005 and again this season.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>We understand that steroids are an illegal substance in the United States, and anybody who uses those substances is obviously at risk, not only under our policies but more importantly, under the laws of the United States,&quot; Manfred said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>Talks on a compromise of seizing only 10 samples failed and the fight continues.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>Greg Anderson, Bonds' personal trainer, was among four men convicted in the BALCO steroid distribution scandal.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="39" label="Bonds trainer Greg Anderson was charged or sentenced concerning steroid distribution" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>The Government Reform Committee was hearing from six subpoenaed players, including Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, along with commissioner Bud Selig and other baseball executives, medical experts and the parents of two amateur athletes who committed suicide after taking steroids.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>Citing unnamed sources within the sport, the newspaper reported that major league commissioner Bud Selig is considering a suspension for the San Francisco Giants star among a wide range of possible responses.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>In a letter sent this week to players union head Donald Fehr, Selig proposed a 100-game ban for a second offense.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="19,43,48"><scu uid="9" label="Suspensions will be increased to 100 for a second offense" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>A congressional committee is looking into Palmeiro's reported claim as part of an investigation into whether he committed perjury when he emphatically denied ever using steroids at a hearing before Congress in March.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="20,40"><scu uid="20" label="Palmiero denied intentionally taking the drug" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>The chairman of a Congressional panel looking into steroid use in Major League Baseball chided the sport's leaders Thursday for being uncooperative and urged star players subpoenaed his hearing to &quot;take public responsibility&quot; for their actions.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="9" sums="13,14,22,29,36,37,44,55,6"><scu uid="31" label="Congressional investigators chided Major League Baseball leaders for being uncooperative regarding steroid use" weight="1"/><scu uid="32" label="Congressional investigators urged star players to take public responsibility for their actions" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>&quot;Steroid users cheat the game.</line><line>&quot;Third offenders should be banned permanently.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>The US Congress has launched an undercover probe into illegal steroid use in Major League Baseball as well as other professional and amateur sports, a senior member of Congress said Sunday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="10" sums="21,29,33,36,40,44,48,49,55,8"><scu uid="1" label="Congress has launched an undercover probe " weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>The NFL has been testing for steroids for 15 years and has suspended 54 active players, an average of 3.6 per year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>Conte pleaded guilty in July to money laundering and a steroid distribution charge; dozens of counts were dropped.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>It would definitely be a deterrent.&quot;</line><line>&quot;I don't think all of them are saints either.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051018.0568"><line>Heredia is the second player to be suspended since the end of the 2005 regular season.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>MLB did not ban performance-enhancing substances until after the 2002 season.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>With 569 homers and 3,020 hits in his 19-year career, Palmeiro was believed to be headed for the Hall of Fame.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>The players also may argue that they made the unprecedented move of re-opening the collective bargaining agreement in January to strengthen the steroid proposal.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051018.0568"><line>The office of the commissioner announced Heredia's 10-day ban on Tuesday.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Minor leaguers not on 40-man, big-league rosters are not protected by the Players' Association.</line><line>The collective bargaining agreement doesn't expire until after the 2006 season.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>Baseball bosses and union leaders objected.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050430.0625"><line>Reached Saturday, Fehr said the union was not yet prepared to discuss Selig's proposal.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>James Valente, BALCO's vice president, was sentenced to probation after pleading guilty to reduced charges of steroid distribution.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050317.0820"><line>But I think they misjudged our seriousness of purpose,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>The policy was revised this season to subject players to unlimited testing and to punish first offenders.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>The book claims Anderson helped Bonds take a wide range of performance-enhancing drugs during seasons when the sport had no doping tests, not bound by World Anti-Doping Agency rules.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>It has threatened to institute an independent, all-sports drug-testing system unless baseball strengthens its policy.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="18,32"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>US chemist Patrick Arnold, 39, has pleaded innocent to charges of conspiring to distribute performance-enhancing drugs to athletes.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>The Orioles sent Palmeiro to his home in Texas earlier this month to rehab an injured knee.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>The report also said a ruling could be made before the Giants' April 3 season opener.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050922.0635"><line>Major League Baseball star Rafael Palmeiro may not be the only Baltimore Oriole in hot water after he told an arbitration panel that a teammate provided him with an unknown substance.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="51"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>In a letter to the players' union, baseball commissioner Bud Selig has admitted that the newly revised steroid policy is not enough.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="13,14,25,37,43,51,6"><scu uid="3" label="Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig admitted the League's policy is not strong enough" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>&quot;I think it is a good start, but we consider steroid abuse to still be rampant and we're going to have a lot more to say,&quot; the Virginia Republican said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051018.1105"><line>He must spend three months behind bars and three months in home confinement.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>The 2003 tests were taken as an anonymous study to judge the level of the steroid problem in the sport, results finishing well above the five percent level needed to create a punishable steroid testing program in 2004.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>We are doing other investigations undercover into professional and amateur sports,&quot; said Representative Tom Davis, chairman of the House Government Reform Committee, who last week called some of baseball's most fabled sluggers before a daylong hearing on steroid use in the sport.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060316.0376"><line>Prompted by an upcoming book about Barry Bonds, an anti-doping U.S. congressman wrote a letter on Wednesday asking Major League Baseball commissioner Bud Selig about his role in policing steroid use from 1998-02.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="8" sums="0,10,12,19,23,25,42,44"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060309.0520"><line>Selig's initial response after reading the book excerpts in Sports Illustrated was &quot;Why am I not surprised now?&quot;, the Tribune reported, adding that Selig has said, &quot;It's even worse than I thought&quot; about Bonds.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>A top baseball official with Major League Baseball said they were caught off guard by news of the probe.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="12,32"><scu uid="30" label="News of the Congressional probe surprised MLB officials" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>Instead of a 60-day suspension for third-time offenders, Selig wants a lifetime ban.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>The union argues the government should not be able to take records for hundreds of athletes, only from 10 with links to the BALCO case that were outlined in a search warrant - including stars Barry Bonds, Jason Giambi and Gary Sheffield.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050320.0310"><line>&quot;We've held other hearings on drug abuse, but nobody comes to them.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20051119.0193"><line>Lawyers from the US Attorney's office and the baseball union argued in a San Francisco court hearing last Tuesday over granting access for prosecutors in the ongoing BALCO steroid case that has already produced four convictions.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050430.0143"><line>&quot;I thought we already negotiated this,&quot; said Rockies star Todd Helton.</line></document></collection>